State Law reference— Authority of cities and counties to license self-service motor fuel dispensing pumps, O.C.G.A. § 36-60-1; certain persons required to provide proof of state licensure before issuance of city or county business license, O.C.G.A. § 36-60-6; limitations regarding persons performing investigations related to city and county business licenses, O.C.G.A. § 36-60-9; taxation of insurers, O.C.G.A. § 33-8-1 et seq.; licensing and taxation of certain businesses, O.C.G.A. § 48-13-1 et seq.; municipal and county occupation taxes for certain traveling salespersons, merchants, and dealers, O.C.G.A. § 48-5-354.
ARTICLE I. - IN GENERAL 

Sec. 10-1. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms and phrases, when used in this chapter, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
Administrative fee means the component of the occupation tax which approximates the reasonable cost or handling and processing the occupation tax. 
Administrator means the city clerk who may be assisted by employees of the clerk's office. 
Employee means an individual whose work is performed under the direction and supervision of the employer and whose employer withholds social security contributions, federal income tax, or state income tax from the individual's compensation or whose employer issues to such individual for purposes of documenting compensation a form W-2, but not a form 1099. 
Location or office means any structure or vehicle where a business, profession, or occupation is conducted, but shall not include a temporary or construction work site which serves a single customer or project, or a vehicle used for sales or delivery by a business or practitioner of a profession. 
Occupation tax means a tax levied for revenue purposes on persons, partnerships, corporations or other entities for engaging in an occupation, profession or business in the city. 
Occupation tax certificate means a document issued by the city acknowledging payment of the occupation tax and administrative fee. 
Practitioners of professions and occupations means those individuals listed in O.C.G.A. § 48-13-9(c)(1)—(18) but does not include a practitioner who is an employee of a business if such business pays an occupation tax. 
Regulatory fee means a fee that approximates the cost of regulatory activity by the city. 
Regulatory fee certificate means a document issued by the city acknowledging payment of a regulatory fee. 
(Ord. of 12-12-1994, § 1(7-1-1); Ord. of 12-11-1995, § 7-1-1(D))
Sec. 10-2. - Applicability of chapter. 
This chapter is applicable not only to those business entities specifically mentioned herein, but also to businesses that may be the topic of other chapters of this Code to the extent this chapter includes regulations not included in those chapters. The licensing provisions of this chapter shall apply to all businesses in the city, to the extent provided herein and permitted by state law; provided, however, that if a chapter of this Code provides a different licensing procedure for a specific type of business enterprise, the specific procedure for that enterprise shall be followed. 
Sec. 10-3. - Information to be collected and provided to state department of revenue. 
(a)	Any person who performs any business, occupation or profession subject to an occupation tax or regulatory fee under O.C.G.A. § 48-13-1 et seq. or this chapter is required to provide the city the following information when paying such occupation tax or regulatory fee: 
(1)	The legal name of the business;
(2)	Any associated trade names for the business;
(3)	The mailing address for the business;
(4)	The actual physical address of each location of the business, if it is different than the mailing address; 
(5)	The North American Industry Classification System Code (NAICS) applicable to such business; and 
(6)	The sales and use tax identification number assigned to the business by the state department of revenue, if the business is required by law to have such a number. 
(b)	The information required by this section will be provided by the city to the state department of revenue electronically, pursuant to state law and rule, within 30 days after receiving the payment of occupation taxes or regulatory fees. Refusal by any person to provide the information required by this section will also be reported to the state department of revenue. 
(Res. of 3-14-2011)
Secs. 10-4—10-24. - Reserved. 
