ARTICLE IX. - PRECIOUS METAL DEALERS 

Sec. 10-259. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms and phrases, when used in this article, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
Buyer of precious metal or gem stones means any person, firm or corporation, whether as owner, agent or employee and whether a resident of the city or not, who engages in the business of purchasing precious metals or gem stones or articles containing any precious metal or gem stone from members of the general public for resale to brokers, dealers or melters. 
Gem stones, as used herein, means diamonds, rubies, emeralds or sapphires. 
Precious metals, as used herein, means gold, silver or platinum or any metal containing gold, silver or platinum. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-2)
Sec. 10-260. - License required. 
It is unlawful for a buyer of precious metals and gem stones to engage in such business within the city without first obtaining a license therefor in compliance with the provisions of this article. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-1)
Sec. 10-261. - Written application. 
Applicants for a license pursuant to this article, whether a person, firm or corporation, shall file with the city clerk a written application under oath, signed by the applicant if an individual, by all partners if a partnership, and by the president of a corporation and showing as follows: 
(1)	The name or names of the person or persons having the management of the applicant's business during the time that it is proposed that it will be carried on within the city; the local address or addresses of such person or persons while engaged in such business; the permanent address of such person or persons; the capacity in which such person or persons will act (that is, whether as proprietor, agent or otherwise); the name and address of the person, firm or corporation for whose account the business will be carried on, if any; and if a cooperation, the name of the state in which the same is incorporated; 
(2)	The place or places within the city where it is proposed to carry on the applicant's business and the length of time during which it is proposed that such business will be conducted; 
(3)	Credentials from the person, firm or corporation for which the applicant proposes to do business, authorizing the applicant to act as representative; and 
(4)	Such other reasonable information as to the identity and character of the person or persons having the management or supervision of the business and the manner of doing business as the city council may deem proper in order to fulfill the purpose of this article in the protection of the public interest. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-3)
Sec. 10-262. - Bond required. 
Before any license shall be issued pursuant to this article, the applicant shall file with the city council a bond binding the applicant to the city in the full sum of $10,000.00, executed by the applicant as principal and by a surety approved by the city council, conditioned that the applicant shall comply fully with the ordinances of the city and state law governing the conduct of such business and will pay all judgments rendered against the applicant for any violation of such ordinances or statutes. Action on the bond may be brought in the name of the city in its behalf. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-4)
Sec. 10-263. - City clerk appointed agent for service of process. 
Before any license shall be issued pursuant to this article, the applicant shall file with the city clerk an instrument appointing the clerk of the city council as his true and lawful agent for services of process upon the applicant or for the performance of the conditions of the bond or for any breach thereof. Immediately upon service of process upon the clerk of the city as herein provided, the clerk shall send to the licensee at his last known address, by registered mail, a copy of such process. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-5)
Sec. 10-264. - Posting of license. 
The license issued pursuant to this article shall be posted conspicuously in the place of business named therein. In the event that the applicant shall desire to do business in more than one place within the city, separate licenses shall be purchased and issued for each place of business, and shall be posted conspicuously in each place of business. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-6)
Sec. 10-265. - Fee. 
Licensees under this article shall pay a license fee in the amount provided in the city fee schedule for each calendar year or portion of year in which the licensee shall engage in business, for each business location within the city. Licenses pursuant to this article shall be nontransferable, and further, the license fee shall be nonrefundable. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-7)
Sec. 10-266. - Daily record of transactions. 
Every buyer of precious metals and gem stones shall maintain a daily record in which shall be entered in legible English at the time of each transaction the following information: 
(1)	The date and time of day of the transaction;
(2)	The name of the person conducting the transaction;
(3)	The name, age, address and race of the seller, a description of the general appearance and estimated height and weight of the seller; and the distinctive number from the seller's driver's license or other similar identification card; 
(4)	A full identification and description of the article or articles including kind, style, material, color, design, and kind and number of stones in jewelry, if any, and all identifying marks and numbers inscribed thereon; 
(5)	The price paid for each item;
(6)	The number of the check issued for the purchase price if payment is made by check; and 
(7)	The signature of the customer.
(Code 1989, § 7-7-8)
Sec. 10-267. - Corrections to record. 
Entries required by the foregoing section shall appear in chronological order in ink. No blank lines may be left between entries. No obliterations, alterations, or erasures may be made. Corrections shall be made by drawing a line of ink through the entry without destroying its legibility. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-9)
Sec. 10-268. - Inspections. 
The complete daily record of each day's transactions, required herein above, shall be open to the inspection of any duly authorized law enforcement officer during the ordinary hours of business or at any reasonable time. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-10)
Sec. 10-269. - Nontransfer period after purchase. 
Every buyer of precious metal or gem stones shall retain possession of each article or item purchased in the city for at least 30 days following each purchase of metals, and ten days for coins. It is unlawful for any buyer of precious metals or gem stones to alter in any matter or to transfer possession of, any article or item purchased in the city within a period of 30 days for metals or ten days for coins, or less, after purchase. In the event any article or item so purchased shall be removed from the city limits within a period of 30 days for metals and ten days for the coins, after purchase, the buyer of precious metals or gem stones shall notify the chief of police in writing, prior to such removal, of the precise location and address to which the article or item shall be removed and shall consent to inspection of the same by the chief of police or any duly authorized law enforcement officer at such location. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-11)
Sec. 10-270. - Revocation of license. 
(a)	The license issued pursuant to this article may be revoked by the mayor and city council, after notice and hearing, for any of the following causes: 
(1)	Any fraud, misrepresentation or false statement contained in the application for license;
(2)	Any fraud, misrepresentation or false statement made in connection with any purchase transaction; 
(3)	Failure to maintain the daily record as required hereinabove;
(4)	Any other violation of this article; or
(5)	Conducting the business license under this article in any unlawful manner or in such a manner as to constitute a breach of the peace or to constitute a menace to the health, safety or general welfare of the public. 
(b)	Notice of hearing for revocation of a license shall be given in writing, setting forth specifically the grounds of the complaint and the time and place of the hearing. The notice shall be served on the licensee by handing the same personally to the person in charge of the licensee's business, or by mailing the same, postage prepaid, to the license at his last-known address at least five days prior to the date set for the hearing. 
(c)	The giving of such notice shall suspend the license pending the outcome of the hearing, and business operations under the license shall cease. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-12)
Sec. 10-271. - Violations. 
It is unlawful for any buyer of precious metals or gem stones to commit any of the following acts: 
(1)	Fail to make an entry of any material matter in his daily record;
(2)	Make any false entry therein;
(3)	Falsify, obliterate or destroy such daily record or remove the same from his place of business; 
(4)	Refuse to allow any duly authorized law enforcement officer to inspect such daily record or any goods in his possession, during the ordinary hours of business or at any reasonable time; or 
(5)	Fail to comply with this article in any other particular.
(Code 1989, § 7-7-13)
Sec. 10-272. - Confidentiality. 
All records in connection with the operation of the purchase of the articles referred to herein will be kept confidential by the city police department and will not be released to any person, firm or corporation without a court order. 
(Code 1989, § 7-7-15)
Secs. 10-273—10-292. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE X. - PAWNSHOPS 

FOOTNOTE(S):
--- (6) --- 
State Law reference— Junk dealers, O.C.G.A. § 43-22-1; pawnbrokers generally, O.C.G.A. § 44-12-130 et seq.; local regulation of pawnbrokers, O.C.G.A. §§ 44-12-135, 44-12-136.
Sec. 10-293. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms and phrases, when used in this article, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
Employee means any person employed or allowed to perform duties, whether or not such person receives a salary, wages or compensation or consideration, but not including the person covered on the license or renewal application. 
Goods, whenever used herein, shall carry its normal meaning, and further, it should be construed in the broadest sense allowable and should include all forms of personal property. 
Owner means any person, partner or stockholder owning 25 percent or more of a business. 
Pawnshop means any business which shall, in any manner, lend or advance money or other things for profit on the pledge of possession of personal property, or other valuable things other than securities or written evidences of indebtedness, or which deals in the purchasing of personal property or other valuable things on condition of selling the same back to the seller at a stipulated price. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-1; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-1)
Sec. 10-294. - Licenses required. 
Every person doing business in the city as a pawnshop as defined herein, prior to commencing business, shall make proper application for and receive the appropriate business license or licenses as set forth herein. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-2; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-2)
Sec. 10-295. - Application for license and permit. 
(a)	Applicants for license or permit shall file a written, sworn application on a form provided by the city clerk, signed by the applicant if an individual, by the partner making application if a partnership, or by the president if a corporation, with the clerk of the city showing: 
(1)	The name or address of the principals, agents and employees of the applicant's business during the time that it is proposed that it will be carried on in the city, the local address or addresses of such person or persons; capacity in which such person or persons will act (as proprietor, agent, employee or otherwise); the name and the address of the person, firm or corporation for whose account the business will be carried on, if any; and if a corporation, under the laws of what state it is incorporated; 
(2)	The fingerprints of the principals, agents or employees of the applicant's business and other evidence which establishes to the satisfaction of the city clerk, subject to the approval of the mayor and council, the good character of such persons to carry on the business; 
(3)	The place or places in the city where it is proposed to carry on the applicant's business, the zoning district at the place or places, and the length of time during which it is proposed that the business shall be conducted; 
(4)	The place or places, other than the permanent place of business of the applicant, where the applicant within the six months preceding the date of the application conducted any other type of business, stating the nature thereof and giving the post office and street address or office in which such business was conducted; 
(5)	A brief statement of the nature and the character of the advertising done or proposed to be done in order to attract customers; 
(6)	Whether or not the person or persons having the management or supervision of the applicant's business have been convicted of a crime or violations of any municipal ordinance, the nature of such offense and the punishment assessed therefor; 
(7)	Credentials from the person, firm or corporation for which the applicant proposes to do business, authorizing the applicant to act as such representative; and 
(8)	Such other information as to the identity or character of the person or persons having the management or supervision of the applicant's business or the method or plan of doing such business as the city clerk may deem proper to fulfill the purpose of this article in the protection of the public good. 
(b)	The application shall state thereon that, "It is unlawful for any person to make a false statement on this application." Any false statement made on the application form will be cause to revoke the license issued thereunder and also shall constitute a violation of state law. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-3; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-3)
Sec. 10-296. - Exclusions; exceptions. 
Businesses which limit the purchase of used valuables to the acceptance of trade-ins for credit for new goods or the dispensing of refunds in regard to valuables previously purchased from the business, shall not be required to be licensed as prescribed by this article nor to be covered under the provisions of this article. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-4; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-4)
Sec. 10-297. - Employee permit. 
Each person authorized or allowed to conduct any place of business covered under this article shall be considered an employee and must have an approved license or an employee permit, and this permit must be displayed along with the business license in accordance with license display requirements. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-5; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-5)
Sec. 10-298. - Business license fee. 
All businesses licensed hereunder shall pay a license fee per calendar year in the amount provided in the city fee schedule. Any co-owner, agent, employee or any other persons authorized to transact business, other than the licensee, shall be required to have employee permits for each license under which he operates or transacts business. There shall be no fee for employee permits issued under this section. Licenses and permits issued hereunder shall be a personal privilege and shall not be transferable, except that employee permits may be transferred from one licensed business to another. There shall be no proration or refund of any license fee. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-6; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-6)
Sec. 10-299. - Character qualifications. 
No license or employee permit shall be issued to or renewed for any person who conducts or is employed in a business in which such owner or employee has, within ten years of issuance or renewal, been convicted of, or pled guilty or nolo contendere to, any felony involving any federal or state offense or any federal or state misdemeanor involving theft-related offenses, unless a longer time has been ordered by a court of competent jurisdiction. The licensee will submit the identity of all owners and employees to the city clerk on a continuing basis as changes occur. This information is to be forwarded to the city police department for the purpose of allowing a complete check in order that these character qualifications are fulfilled prior to the issuance or renewal of any license or permit issued hereunder. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-7; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-7)
Sec. 10-300. - Location of businesses. 
All businesses licensed hereunder shall be located in strict compliance with city zoning regulations and at a location with an identifiable street address, which shall be stated on the license or renewal application along with other required information; and no business licensed hereunder shall change its address without giving advance notice to the city clerk and the city police department, and receiving approval of the change, the approval being granted if the new location complies with this article and the city zoning regulations. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-8; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-8)
Sec. 10-301. - Records to be kept; inspection; violations. 
(a)	All pawnshops, in addition to other records, shall keep books wherein shall be entered an accurate description of all property received by or pledged or sold to them. Such description shall include the brand name of the article, any identifying mark, number, initial, social security number or name of any person or company and a statement of the kind of material of which it is made. A permanent bound set of the pawn tickets shall constitute the book required by this article. 
(b)	In such books there shall be entered also the name, age, address, signature, and identification number from a driver's license or similar identification of the person by who same was delivered, deposited or sold, the name of the agent or employee receiving the item, the time when such transaction occurred, the price paid for the goods purchased and the check number issued, if applicable. 
(c)	All books and records required by this article and items pledged or sold hereunder shall at all times be subject to inspection and examination by any city, county, state or federal law enforcement officer. Any person engaged in any business licensed hereunder, who shall fail or refuse to keep the records as provided in this article, or who shall make false entries concerning the transaction or who shall fail or refuse to permit an inspection by any of the aforementioned law enforcement officers of the records and of the property deposited with or sold to such person shall be guilty of a violation of this article. 
(d)	Any licensee found to have violated this section shall receive a written warning upon such finding. If a licensee is found to have violated this subjection a second time, the licensee's license shall be suspended for a period of two years and no person living at the same address as the licensee may become licensed under this article without first showing to the satisfaction of the city that the business will be totally separate from, independent of, and unaffiliated with the licensee whose license has been suspended. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-9; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-9)
Sec. 10-302. - Standard forms required. 
All businesses licensed hereunder shall use a standard form for pawn and a standard form for purchase, and no ticket may be used for a dual purpose. Standard forms may differ only by the name of the business and business address. The design of this form shall be provided by the police department and the forms shall be numbered and chronologically used and sent to the police department. Each number missing from the chronological sequence shall be considered a separate violation of this article. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-10; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-10)
Sec. 10-303. - Weekly report. 
(a)	Every licensee shall prepare a daily report for the city police department, in such form as may be prescribed by the police department, of all property pledged to or bought by the licensee during the preceding 24 hours ending at 8:00 p.m. on the effective date of the report. In addition to any other information required by the police department, the report shall disclose: 
(1)	The name and address of the licensee;
(2)	Time of transaction;
(3)	Serial numbers of pawn tickets;
(4)	Full description of articles, including kind, style, material, color, design, kind and number of stones in jewelry, and all identifying names, marks, and numbers; 
(5)	A description of persons pledging, selling, or pawning; including name, address, information from such person's driver's license or government-issued identification, including weight, height, and eye color; and 
(6)	Serial numbers on items.
(b)	Insufficient or incomplete reports shall be rejected.
(c)	Any licensee or employee who fails or refuses to prepare and keep reports as provided in this section or makes false entries concerning a transaction or who fails or refuses to permit an inspection or examination of the report by any police officer, designated by the chief of police to conduct such inspections, shall constitute a violation of this Code, which shall be punishable as provided in this article. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-11; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-11)
Sec. 10-304. - Identification required. 
Each licensee shall require any person pawning, pledging, or selling an article or articles to display his government-issued identification that, at a minimum, contains a photograph, date of birth, height, weight, eye color, race and gender, as well as the identification number, driver's license number or social security number of the person, the type of identification and the name of the city council issuing such identification. The licensee shall record all of the above information from such identification. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-12; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-12)
Sec. 10-305. - Purchased articles not to be disposed of for seven days after acquisition. 
Every business licensed hereunder shall hold on the premises designated in the license for doing business every item purchased for at least ten working days not including holidays or weekends, before disposing of same by sale, transfer or shipment. The provisions of this section shall not apply to items purchased from licensed wholesalers in the normal course of business. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-13; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-13)
Sec. 10-306. - Pawned articles not to be disposed of for 30 days after acquisition. 
Every business licensed hereunder shall hold pawned goods for at least 30 days, unless redeemed by the owner or on authority of the owner, before disposing of same by sale, transfer, shipment or otherwise. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-14; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-14)
Sec. 10-307. - Display of goods pledged or purchased. 
(a)	For a period of ten working days from the date of purchase and 30 days from the date of pledge, unless redeemed by or by authority of the person who pledged the goods, all goods purchased or pawned, and required to be included in the records and reports specified in this article, shall be kept on the licensed premises. A copy of the pawn ticket or the number of the original pawn ticket shall be affixed to each item that is subject to the provisions of this section. 
(b)	Any person desiring to examine any merchandise shall first file with the city police department an incident report or stolen property report and upon giving notice, in writing to the owner or employee, which notice shall include a full description of the stolen items including all identifying characteristics, the person's name, address, identification and signature, such individual shall be allowed to examine any merchandise of the type described in the request on the premises. 
(c)	Such written information shall be kept in sequential, dated order in a permanent file or book. This record shall be kept in addition to all other records required herein. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-15; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-15)
Sec. 10-308. - Alteration. 
Any items required to be kept or displayed under the provisions of this article shall be kept in their original form as they existed when first purchased, and their physical characteristics shall not be altered in any numerical or material manner. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-16; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-16)
Sec. 10-309. - Erasures or obliterations or write-overs or type-overs are not allowed. 
No persons licensed hereunder shall erase, obliterate, type over, write over or in any way cause the original entry on the records required by this article to become illegible. All pawn or purchase tickets filled out in error shall be sent to the city police department in their numbered order along with the weekly reports and shall have the word "VOID" typed or written across the front. Such entry shall not be used to cause the original entry to be illegible. If an error is made, and the ticket is still to be used, then a single line shall be drawn through the incorrect entry. This line shall not cause the original entry to be illegible, and the correct information entry shall be made on the next available area. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-17; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-17)
Sec. 10-310. - Records maintained for four years. 
The record for each pawn or purchase transaction regulated by this article shall be maintained for a period of not less than four years from date of the transaction. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-18; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-18)
Sec. 10-311. - Dealing with minors. 
It is unlawful for any person licensed hereunder to receive in pawn or in purchase any goods of any character or of any description from any person who has not attained the age of 17 years. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-19; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-19)
Sec. 10-312. - Hours of operation. 
All businesses licensed hereunder shall close their establishments and cease transacting any business no later than 11:00 p.m. each day and begin their operation and commence transacting business at no time before 7:00 a.m. each day. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-20; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-20)
Sec. 10-313. - Business transactions to be conducted in licensed premises; exception. 
(a)	No business transactions by any business licensed hereunder shall be conducted outside the building designated as the normal place to conduct transactions unless the business does not have a building. 
(b)	The term "business transaction" means any part of a business including the inspection or appraisal of any goods when it is possible for such goods to be taken outside the building where transactions are normally made ("possible" being here used in the broadest sense); and no person other than those possessing a license or employee permit shall be allowed to conduct any form of business transaction either inside the establishment or on any part of outside land area covered under address of the license. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-21; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-21)
Sec. 10-314. - Articles with serial numbers removed or altered may not be accepted. 
No business licensed hereunder shall accept any article which has had the serial number altered, obliterated or removed from such article or which the person who is making the business transaction knows should have a serial number on it. Licensees shall immediately report any attempted business transaction of this nature to the city police department. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-22; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-22)
Sec. 10-315. - Compliance with records requirements required for pawn acceptance. 
No business licensed hereunder shall take any item in pawn or purchase or take full possession or title thereto, without entering such transaction of such goods on his books and on the standard forms as provided for in this article. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-23; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-23)
Sec. 10-316. - Ownership of other pawn business in other town or same town. 
Any owner of a business licensed hereunder shall not transfer goods from one business, where he has a minority or majority ownership, to another business without the goods meeting all regulations of the ordinances of the city regarding pawnshops. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-24; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-24)
Sec. 10-317. - Violations; penalties. 
(a)	Any person licensed hereunder who shall do any of the following act shall be in violation of this article: 
(1)	Fail to make any entry of any required item in the permanent record book;
(2)	Make any false entry therein;
(3)	Falsify, obliterate, destroy or remove from his place of business such permanent record book so that information is illegible; 
(4)	Refuse to allow any duly authorized law enforcement officer to inspect such permanent record book, or any goods in his possession, during the ordinary hours of business or any reasonable time, or refuse to allow any member of the general public to inspect goods in his possession being held under pawn or purchase within seven days of purchase and 30 days of the item being pawned, during ordinary hours of business; 
(5)	Fail to maintain a record of each pawn or purchase transaction for at least four years;
(6)	Violate any other provisions of this article;
(b)	Operation of any business hereunder in violation of any provision of this article shall constitute a separate offense for each day of operation. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-25; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-25)
Sec. 10-318. - Inspection. 
As a condition of the granting of the license hereunder, every licensee agrees to allow any duly authorized law enforcement officer, pursuant to his official duties, to be and remain about the licensed premises without the formality of a warrant, provided the officer does not interfere in the licensee's operation. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-26; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-26)
Sec. 10-319. - Nonformed precious metals. 
It is unlawful for any person licensed hereunder to purchase precious metals in a melted, smelted or nonformed state unless the purchase is from a registered dealer in precious metals. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-27; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-27)
Sec. 10-320. - Stolen items. 
Every person licensed hereunder shall, immediately, upon request, turn over to the police department every item believed by the police department to be a stolen item. The police department shall furnish a property receipt, including the case number to the dealer surrendering such item, and such item shall be returned to the dealer only after it has been determined that such item is not stolen. If it is determined such item is stolen, it shall be returned to its lawful owner. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-28; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-28)
Sec. 10-321. - Sale of prohibited weapons. 
It is unlawful for any licensee to sell, offer for sale, or expose for sale any weapons, the sale of which are prohibited by city ordinance, state law, or federal law or regulation. Any licensee or employee thereof violating this section shall constitute a violation of this section and shall be punishable as provided in this article. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-29; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-29)
Sec. 10-322. - Security cameras required. 
(a)	Any establishment which is licensed by the city to engage in the business of operating as a pawnshop and which is open to the public for business any day of the week is required to install security cameras and recording mechanisms of a type and number capable of recording evidentiary quality images for the prosecution of criminal cases, or for such other uses as may be deemed authorized by law. 
(b)	Cameras and recording mechanisms meeting the requirements of this section must be capable of producing a retrievable image on video tape or other medium that can be made a permanent record and can be enlarged through projection or other means. Cameras and recording mechanisms meeting the requirements of this section shall be maintained in proper working order at all times and shall be subject to inspection by the city police department. 
(c)	Security videos must have a shelf life of 15 calendar days from time of daily taping. The security video must be maintained at the licensee's place of business in an unaltered state and be available for inspection by the city police department. 
(d)	In the event that the security cameras and recording mechanisms become inoperative, any licensee or employee thereof shall not be in violation of this section for conducting business if the licensee is diligently pursuing repairs of such system; provided that such repairs must be completed within ten days after such system becomes inoperative. 
(e)	Any licensee or employee thereof violating this section shall constitute a violation of this Code and shall be punishable as provided in this article. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-30; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-30)
Sec. 10-323. - Applicability of and conflict with state law. 
This article is to be construed as consistent with state law. However, these provisions are to be applied in lieu of state law and state fee and registration requirements whenever possible. It is the intent of this law that all duties delegated to the chief law enforcement officer of the city shall be exercised as provided herein. 
(Code 1989, § 7-9-31; Ord. of 6-8-2009, § 7-9-31)
Secs. 10-324—10-349. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE XI. - COIN-OPERATED AMUSEMENT MACHINES 
DIVISION 1. - GENERALLY 

Sec. 10-350. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms, or phrases, when used in this article, shall have the meaning ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
Amusement game room means any location as provided in O.C.G.A. § 16-12-35 where one or more bona fide coin-operated amusement machines are operated that permit noncash redemption as provided in O.C.G.A. § 16-25-35. 
Bona fide coin-operated amusement machine means the same as this term is defined in O.C.G.A. § 48-17-1 and any applicable state regulations. Examples of bona fide coin-operated amusement machines include, but are expressly not limited to, kiddie ride, novelty arcade and video games; pinball, console, crane, claw, pusher, bowling, foosball, table soccer, miniature racetrack, football, golf, target shooting, other shooting gallery, basketball, shuffleboard, skeeball, air hockey and roll down machines; coin-operated pool table or coin-operated billiard table as defined in O.C.G.A. § 43-8-1; and any other similar amusement game, device or machine that can be legally operated in state. The term "bona fide coin-operated amusement machine" does not include coin-operated washing machines or dryers, vending machines that dispense products or services for payment of money, gas and electric meters, pay telephones, pay toilets, cigarette vending machines, coin-operated vending machines, coin-operated scales, coin-operated gumball machines, coin-operated television sets that provide cable or network programming, coin-operated massage beds, or machines that are not legally permitted to be operated in state. 
Location means a business within the city that has complied with the provisions of the ordinances of the city relating to occupation taxes and business licenses. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 3)
Sec. 10-351. - State licenses and permit stickers required. 
Bona fide coin-operated amusement machines may be used in an amusement game room within the city only if the machines are owned by a person who holds a valid master license in accordance with O.C.G.A. § 48-17-2, and each machine offered to the public for play has a valid permit sticker in accordance with O.C.G.A. § 48-17-9. In addition, the business owner where the machines are available for play by the public must pay a location license fee in order to obtain a valid location license in accordance with O.C.G.A. § 48-17-2. The city official in charge of issuing business licenses shall notify the state commissioner of revenue of any observed violation of O.C.G.A. § 48-17-2 or 48-17-9. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 11)
Secs. 10-352—10-375. - Reserved. 
DIVISION 2. - CITY BUSINESS LICENSE 

Sec. 10-376. - Required. 
No person shall engage in the business of an owner or proprietor of an amusement game room without first having obtained a license and without first having paid the applicable occupation tax required under this article. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 4)
Sec. 10-377. - Application; fee. 
Application for a license for operating an amusement game room within the corporate limits of the city shall be made to the city clerk upon a form to be supplied by the city clerk for this purpose. The license application shall be accompanied by a fee in the amount provided in the city fee schedule and shall include the following information: 
(1)	Name, address, and age of the applicant and the date of the application and if a firm, corporation, partnership or association, the principal officers thereof and their addresses; 
(2)	Address or place where the bona fide coin-operated amusement machine or machines are to be offered to the public for play and the other business or businesses operated at that place; 
(3)	Name and address of the owner of the machine or machines and a copy of the owner's master license; 
(4)	Name and address of any other business owned or operated by applicant within the corporate limits of the city; 
(5)	List of any other licenses or permits from the city held by the applicant;
(6)	A statement with regard to whether the persons having the management of or supervision over the applicant's business have been convicted of a crime, misdemeanor or the violation of any city ordinance, the nature of such offense and the punishment assessed therefor; and 
(7)	The proprietors shall list the number of machines to be maintained on the premises.
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 5; Ord. of 3-12-2012, § 5)
Sec. 10-378. - Certain felons may not be licensed; criminal background investigation. 
(a)	No license shall be issued to or renewed for any person who has or employs a person who has, within five years of the issuance or renewal, been convicted of or pled guilty or nolo contendere to, any felony involving any federal or state offense or any federal or state misdemeanor involving drug-related offenses or offenses involving moral turpitude. 
(b)	The applicant will submit the identity of all owners and employees to the permit and license department on a continuing basis as changes occur. This information is to be forwarded to the city police department, for the purpose of allowing a complete check in order that these character qualifications be fulfilled, prior to the issuance or renewal of any license or permit issued hereunder. 
Sec. 10-379. - Revocation. 
(a)	Any license issued hereunder shall be subject to suspension or revocation pursuant to the provisions of this article. 
(b)	If any holder of a license or permit issued pursuant to this article should be engaged in unlawful activities (including acts that would constitute violations of state law, municipal ordinances, municipal zoning regulations, and heating, electrical, health and building codes) and where such unlawful activities are of such nature as to directly or indirectly affect his qualification to conduct the business for which he was licensed or permitted or involves the conduct of such business, the business license or permit may be revoked or suspended in the manner provided herein. 
(c)	If it is reported to the city clerk that a holder of a license obtained under this article is engaged in activities specified in subsection (b) of this section, a preliminary investigation shall be conducted by the city clerk in order to determine whether there is a basis for the reports. If the city clerk's preliminary investigation reveals that there may be a basis for revocation or suspension of the license or permit, the license or permit holder will be notified to appear before the city clerk on a date certain and show cause why his business license or permit should not be suspended or revoked. The license or permit holder may appear in person at the hearing or be represented by counsel. At the conclusion of the hearing, the city clerk, based upon evidence submitted at the hearing, shall enter an order making findings of fact. If the clerk's findings are that the evidence does not authorize disciplinary administrative action, the matter shall be dismissed. If the clerk's findings are that the evidence supports disciplinary administrative action, the clerk shall issue a warning to the licensee or permit holder, suspend the license or permit and probate suspension, suspend the license or permit for up to 30 days, or suspend the license or permit pending a hearing by the mayor and city council on revocation. 
(d)	Within ten days from the date of the order from the city clerk, the licensee or permit holder may appeal the decision of the city clerk by filing a notice of appeal with the mayor and city council. Any decision of the city clerk to suspend pending a hearing by the city council shall automatically be scheduled for a hearing by the mayor and city council no later than 30 days from the date of the suspension. Notice of appeal shall supersede any suspension, pending hearing, except a suspension pending a hearing before the mayor and city council on revocation. The city clerk shall schedule a hearing before the mayor and city council and notify the licensee or permit holder of the time and date of hearing. Either party shall have the right to subpoena witnesses at this hearing. At the conclusion of the hearing, the mayor and city council may affirm, overrule or partially affirm and partially overrule the decision of the city clerk. 
(e)	The mayor and city council are authorized to find in favor of the licensee or permit holder, issue a warning to the licensee or permit holder, suspend the license or permit and probate revocation, revoke the license or permit and probate revocation, suspend the license or permit for a definite period of time, revoke the license or permit, or take any other appropriate action regarding the licensee or permit holder. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 15)
Sec. 10-380. - Licenses nontransferable. 
All businesses that have bona fide coin-operated amusement machines on the premises shall display, in plain view, the current license issued by the city. The issued license shall not be transferred to another owner at the same site within the city. A new owner or proprietor must first obtain a new license if they are going to operate in the same or different location in the city. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 16)
Sec. 10-381. - Display of license. 
Every amusement game room shall post the license issued by the city conspicuously and permanently. 
Secs. 10-382—10-405. - Reserved. 
DIVISION 3. - PREMISES, OPERATION AND OTHER REGULATIONS 

Sec. 10-406. - Occupation tax required. 
No person, firm or corporation shall engage in the business of an owner or proprietor of an amusement game room without first having completed the occupation tax certificate form, paid the required occupational tax and without first having obtained the license required under this article. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 6)
Sec. 10-407. - Gross receipts. 
Every amusement game room shall keep records available for inspection by city officials that set out separately annual gross receipts for the amusement games and the other products and services sold at the location. Income from the amusement game or games shall not constitute more than 50 percent of the income from the location. Compliance with this section requires both the availability of records for inspection and compliance with the 50 percent of income requirement. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 9)
Sec. 10-408. - Location restrictions; waiver. 
Every amusement game room in the city shall comply with the proximity provision for business licensed to sell alcohol set out in O.C.G.A. § 3-3-21. After a hearing, the mayor and council may waive the application of this provision to an individual location if no alcohol is served or sold at such location. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 7)
Sec. 10-409. - Number of machines per location restricted; waiver. 
No amusement game room in the city shall offer to the public more than nine bona fide coin-operated amusement machines offering noncash redemption in accordance with O.C.G.A. § 16-12-35 at the same location. After a hearing, the mayor and council may, after consideration of the nature and character of the business, waive the applicability of this provision to an individual location. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 8)
Sec. 10-410. - Notice requirements. 
Every amusement game room shall post a conspicuous sign with the following or similar words: 
"GEORGIA LAW PROHIBITS GIVING OR RECEIPT OF ANY MONEY FOR WINNING A GAME OR GAMES ON AN AMUSEMENT MACHINE; GIVING OR RECEIPT OF MONEY FOR FREE REPLAYS WON ON AN AMUSEMENT MACHINE; GIVING OR RECEIPT OF MONEY FOR ANY MERCHANDISE, PRIZE, TOY, GIFT CERTIFICATE, OR NOVELTY WON ON ANY AMUSEMENT MACHINE; OR AWARDING ANY MERCHANDISE, PRIZE, TOY, GIFT CERTIFICATE, OR NOVELTY OF A VALUE EXCEEDING $5.00 FOR A SINGLE PLAY OF AN AMUSEMENT MACHINE." 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 10)
Sec. 10-411. - Operating requirements. 
Any business operating as an amusement center hereunder shall be subject to the following regulations: 
(1)	Devices to be kept in plain view; gambling devices prohibited. All machines shall at all times be kept and placed in plain view of and open and accessible to any persons who may frequent or be in any place of business where such machines are kept or used. Nothing in this section shall be construed to authorize, permit or license any gambling device of any nature whatsoever. 
(2)	Inspection. The chief of police shall inspect or cause the inspection of any place or building in which any such machines are operated or set up for operating, and shall inspect, investigate and test such machines as needed. 
(3)	Attendant required. It is unlawful for any proprietor to open his business to the public unless an attendant is present. The attendant shall be of sufficient mental and physical capacity so as to be able to provide aid to patrons if needed or desired. The attendant shall not be less than 18 years of age. 
(4)	Loitering. As used in this section, the term "loitering" means remaining idle in essentially one location and shall include the concepts of spending time idly, loafing or walking about aimlessly, and is unlawful for any person, firm or corporation licensed to operate an amusement center to permit loitering on or in the immediate vicinity of any machine or business premises regulated hereunder in such a manner as to create or cause to be created a danger of a breach of the peace or any disturbance or annoyance to the comfort and repose of any person; obstruct the free passage of pedestrians or vehicles; or obstruct, molest or interfere with any person lawfully in a public place. 
(5)	Shirt and shoes required. All proprietors shall require shirts and shoes to be worn at all times by any person frequenting their premises. 
(6)	Hours of operation. No amusement game room operator may permit coin-operated amusement machines to be used between the hours of 12:00 a.m. midnight and 7:00 a.m. from Monday through Sunday. 
(7)	Alcoholic beverages prohibited. No amusement game room operator shall allow alcoholic beverages to be brought onto his premises by any person. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 14)
Sec. 10-412. - Employees to be informed of applicable law and penalties. 
The owner or proprietor of each amusement game room shall inform every employee of the acts and omissions prohibited by O.C.G.A. § 16-12-35 and by this article and of the penalties for violation of O.C.G.A. § 16-12-35 and this article. 
Secs. 10-413—10-437. - Reserved. 
DIVISION 4. - ADMINISTRATION AND ENFORCEMENT 

Sec. 10-438. - Enforcing officer. 
The chief of police or his designee is hereby designated as the enforcement officer and shall execute all requirements of this article. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 17)
Sec. 10-439. - Penalties for failure to obtain a license. 
Any person who shall begin or carry on any business or occupation for which a license is required by this article without first obtaining the license prescribed in this article shall, upon conviction, be fined in a sum not exceeding $500.00; however, in no event shall a fine be less than $50.00. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 18)
Sec. 10-440. - Penalties for unlawful playing of machines. 
The municipal court of the city is authorized to impose a fine of $250.00 for a first offense, and $500.00 for a second and all subsequent offenses, on any person convicted of receiving money as a reward for the successful play or winning of any bona fide coin-operated amusement machine from any person owning, possessing, controlling or overseeing such bona fide coin-operated amusement machine or any person employed by or acting on behalf of a person owning, possessing, controlling or overseeing a bona fide coin-operated amusement machine. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 13)
Sec. 10-441. - Penalties for violations of state law. 
In addition to the penalties set forth in state law for failure to comply with the provisions of O.C.G.A. § 16-12-35, the owner or operator of an amusement game room, after conviction in a court of competent jurisdiction, and a hearing before the mayor and council, may be subject to the following penalties: 
(1)	First offense. Suspension for not more than six months of the business license for offering any amusement game at the location where the violation occurred. 
(2)	Second offense. Suspension for not more than 12 months of the business license for offering any amusement game at the location where the violation occurred. 
(3)	Third and subsequent offenses. Suspension or permanent revocation of the business license for offering any amusement game at the location where the violation occurred, and suspension of other permits and licenses granted by the city for not more than six months. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 13)
Sec. 10-442. - Penalties for violations of this article. 
(a)	Generally. Penalties for violation of the provisions of this article by the owner or operator of an amusement game room, after conviction in the municipal court of the city are as follows: 
(1)	First offense. Fine not to exceed $500.00 for each violation. 
(2)	Second offense. Fine not to exceed $750.00 for each violation, suspension of the business license for offering any amusement game at the location for not more than three months, or both. 
(3)	Third and subsequent offenses. Fine not to exceed $1,000.00 for each violation, suspension or permanent revocation of the business license for offering any amusement game at the location, or suspension of other permits and licenses granted by the city for not more than six months, or any combination of these penalties. 
(b)	Fines, suspension imposed. The fines listed in the penalties for violation of this article may be imposed by the judge of the municipal court of the city. Suspension or revocation of the business license for offering any amusement game at the location where the violation occurred, and suspension of other permits and licenses granted by the city may also be imposed by the mayor and council after a hearing. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 13)
Sec. 10-443. - Penalties for violation of an order suspending or revoking license. 
Offering one or more bona fide coin-operated amusement machine games in violation of an order suspending or revoking the license for the offering of any amusement game at the location is punishable, after conviction in the municipal court of the city, by a fine not to exceed $1,000.00, imprisonment not to exceed 30 days, or both such fine and imprisonment. 
(Ord. of 11-10-2011, § 13)
